                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d149">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5 Submarines/11: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 28, 1936—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. For the Ambassador or Atherton. Davis’ 165, March 25, 10 p.m.<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d149fn6">See footnote 5, above.</note> In view of the departure of
                    the American Delegates to the Naval Conference, you are hereby authorized to
                    sign, at such time as may be determined, the procès-verbal designed to obtain
                    further accessions to the rules of international law concerning submarine
                    warfare to which the United States as well as the United Kingdom and Japan are
                    now expressly committed under the London Naval Treaty of 1930.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
